ales, United Kingdom","Llanddewi, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llanddewi, Glamorgan, Wales"},"nl":{"1250–1290":"1250–1290","–Male":"Overleden","1254–Female":"1254–Overleden","1273–Male":"1273–Overleden","1275–Female":"1275–Overleden","1304–Female":"1304–Overleden","1226–1266":"1226–1266","1227–Female":"1227–Overleden","1227":"1227","1304":"1304","1226":"1226","1266":"1266","Abt 1275":"circa 1275","about 1249":"circa 1249","1254":"1254","1275":"1275","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","Llandewi, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llanddewi, Glamorgan, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Glamorganshire, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","of Miscin,,, Wales":"Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Llanddewi, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llanddewi, Glamorgan, Wales"},"en":{"1250–1290":"1250–1290","–Male":"Deceased","1254–Female":"1254–Deceased","1273–Male":"1273–Deceased","1275–Female":"1275–Deceased","1304–Female":"1304–Deceased","1226–1266":"1226–1266","1227–Female":"1227–Deceased","1227":"1227","1304":"1304","1226":"1226","1266":"1266","Abt 1275":"about 1275","about 1249":"about 1249","1254":"1254","1275":"1275","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","Llandewi, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llanddewi, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Glamorganshire, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","of Miscin,,, Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Llanddewi, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llanddewi, Glamorgan, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Carodoc","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Respelling of <i>Caradog</i>, an ancient Celtic name apparently derived from the root <i>cār</i> ‘love’. This name was borne by a British chieftain of the 1st century  ad  in the Latinized form <i>Caractacus</i>, son of Cunobelinos."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]},{"name":"Leuan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Iefan","meanings":["Later form of   Ieuan ."]},{"name":"Ifan","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Carodoc Ap Leuan 8th Lord of Cardigan was born in 1250, in Glamorgan, Wales, his father, Leuan Evan ap Meuric of Ystrad, was 24 and his mother, Cecilia Clark, was 24. He married Alice Welsh in 1270, in Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died in 1290, in 